#ifndef FACTORIAL_H
#define FACTORIAL_H

// Simple factorial function
int factorial(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) return 1;
    else return n * factorial(n - 1);
}

#endif // FACTORIAL_H
```

### Writing a Test Case Using gtest

For our test case, assuming you have Google Test set up in your project, we will write a test fixture to test our `factorial` function.

**factorial_test.cpp**
```cpp
#include "factorial.h"
#include <gtest/gtest.h>

// Define a test fixture class
class FactorialTest : public ::testing::Test {
protected:
    void SetUp() override {
        // Setup code can be added here. It will run before each test in this fixture.
    }

    void TearDown() override {
        // Cleanup code can be added here. It will run after each test in this fixture.
    }

    // You can add data members that can be used in your tests here.
};

// Test cases
TEST_F(FactorialTest, HandlesZeroInput) {
    EXPECT_EQ(factorial(0), 1);
}

TEST_F(FactorialTest, HandlesPositiveInput) {
    EXPECT_EQ(factorial(5), 120);
}

TEST_F(FactorialTest, HandlesOneAsInput) {
    EXPECT_EQ(factorial(1), 1);
}

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
    ::testing::InitGoogleTest(&argc, argv);
    return RUN_ALL_TESTS();
}
```

In this example, `FactorialTest` derives from `::testing::Test`, provided by gtest for creating test fixtures. The `SetUp` and `TearDown` member functions are overridden to provide common setup and cleanup tasks, though they're not specifically utilized in this basic example.

`TEST_F()` defines a test case within the `FactorialTest` fixture. `HandlesZeroInput`, `HandlesPositiveInput`, and `HandlesOneAsInput` are test cases that check for the correct computation of factorials for specific inputs.

